All Classes

Class Description
Board
Implements a two dimensional grid of cell "states", ranging from 0 up to (and including) 9.
BoardCanvas  
BoardFrame  
BoardView
Implements a view of the board, from which it is impossible to actually change the board.
CellDecayGameOfLife  
CellDecayTests
These test Conway's original rules for the Game of life in various ways.
ClockThread
The Clock Thread is responsible for producing a consistent "pulse" which is used to update the game state, and refresh the display.
ContinueGenerationRule
This should implements a over-population rule: "Any live cell with two live neighbors continues in stasis to the next generation"
ConwayAbstractRule
Implements a standard class for implementing the standard rules for Conway's game of life.
ConwaysOverpopulationRule
This should implements Conway's rule for overproduction: "Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies, as if by over-population"
ConwaysReproductionRule
This should implement Conway's rule for reproduction: "Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell, as if by reproduction"
ConwaysUnderpopulationRule
This should implement Conway's rule for underproduction: "Any life cell with fewer than two live neighbors die, as if caused by under-population"
GameOfLife  
GameOfLifeTests
These test Conway's original rules for the Game of life in various ways.
HappinessAgeingRule
This should implements a happiness rule: "Any live cell with exactly three live neighbors gets younger, as if by happiness"
OverpopulationAgeingRule
This should implements a over-population rule: "Any live cell with more than three live neighbors gets older, as if by over-population
Rule
Provides a concept of a rule for controlling cell creation / destruction in the simulation.
Simulation
Implements an abstract version of Conway's game of life where the rules for birth's and deaths are customisable.
UnderpopulationAgeingRule
This should implements a under-population rule: "Any live cell with fewer than two live neighbors gets older, as if caused by under-population"
